Inflation in Europe has skidded on food
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro zone, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 countries of the euro area was greater than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent cent was recorded, said the statistics office of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts pointed to just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate, saying that the decrease in interest, with the growth in commodity prices and the fall in the rate of unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: &quot;we must dissuade&quot; inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record for the past twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the Eurozone took off due to rapidly rising food and energy prices.
Grain futures quotes rose 88 percent and soybean prices also hit their highest since 1973.
The price of edible oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil has risen by 52 percent, and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will drop from 2.1, this year to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3 to 4 months the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Since 2002, he currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Poll Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of opposition voters, support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP. (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent across the population.
Of loyal voters certain to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who judged the country&#39;s economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, it amounts to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population foresees a worsening and only a tenth foresees an improvement of the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority unseen in previous Gallup polls, thought the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society believing that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after last October&#39;s riots, 35 percent of those polled wanted the government and prime minister to remain in office, currently that rate is only 20 percent. The relative majority (33 percent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of those polled answered that they would definitely vote and the remaining 20 percent said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a &quot;legislative election to be held next Sunday&quot;, only 55 percent of those polled would certainly participate and an additional 15 percent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would not be in doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education tuition fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters, respectively, would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and living expenses at the hospital.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
Hypermarkets located in the Budaörs shopping triangle maintained last year&#39;s average price increase of 16 percent, except that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase in value clearly exceeding one thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, &quot;which had already soared&quot; in large grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Unicum and live fish prices remained almost at last year&#39;s level, however prices for turkey fillet, walnuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, we found bread weighing one kilo at only 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was under 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints including the bottle with deposit.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan have increased them by around 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year&#39;s most expensive basket to this year&#39;s cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent difference while the difference between last year&#39;s cheapest and this year&#39;s most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices rose by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased by 1,206 forints on average, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year&#39;s Christmas prices.
This process perplexed trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he risks losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily basket evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of that of 2006, while the difference between the baskets the cheapest was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the prices of the cheapest increased by 1,284 forints as well.
Bringing the two Christmas seasons together, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH&#39;s data: for some staple foods, the statistics institute has seen a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, of flour and eggs.)
According to the latter&#39;s Daily Basket, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, the suppliers of flour occupy a stronger position than the suppliers of eggs because they succeeded in making accept the brutal increase in prices also by the multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain, they consistently record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at the prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-life foods on pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is lower in the provinces, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for articles of sustainable consumption.
Many hospitals are saving money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center of Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident was discharged from hospital but soon after had to return due to an MRSA infection and since then doctors have not been able to perform major surgery on him due to bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Namely, it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, in other words by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if the antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to the antibiotics, will develop a bacterium which is well resistant to the antibiotics and which will proliferate rapidly in the poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or septicemia, in elderly patients, those with low weight or those with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
It is important not to confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
AS are resistant to antibiotics.
&quot;These patients are isolated, the medical staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have suitable antibiotics to treat them,&quot; said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample taking is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favorable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for the elderly, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only arise if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, ie microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Taking microbiological samples is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, Karolina Böröcz communicated.
Many hospitals are saving money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferate from patient to patient most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, major shortcomings are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSA proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, whereas in terms of an epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving money on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, indicated Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of the MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for the social security funds, which is why we fight everywhere against this infection.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) lists among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The superintendent, author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of intoxication
The official statement relating to the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who ran over a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizzy, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesperson for the Ministry audience of the capital after the relative report has been established.
The report confirmed the first result of the investigation which has already found that the ex-commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd district police station ran over a 55-year-old man who found himself in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, into Kossuth Lajos street in the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not going through the pedestrian crossing.
(Besides, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing does not constitute a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car which initiates a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to hospital.
Following this accident, the superintendent resigned from his post and he asked for his retirement because, according to the communication of the police, this accident upset him a lot.
The investigation into this case is being carried out by the Prosecutor&#39;s Office in charge of investigations in Budapest.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the start with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
400 million additional euros for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian finance minister, and Marta Gajecka, vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed, on Friday in Budapest, three agreements worth a total of 400 million euros concerning a credit to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure, and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of 300 million euros for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, including a credit contract of value of 100 million euros has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The agreement on the credit of 150 million euros also concerns the budgetary financing of projects linked to education.
The EIB has approved a total of 300 million euros for Hungary, the remaining 150 million euros can be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place within the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the initial contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its credits according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment commission.
Bulgaria, paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned towards this country of the Balkans little quoted in the past.
What, where and who buys in this EU market which is still the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the hottest target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the &quot;Golden Sands&quot;, the &quot;Sun Coast&quot;, the old Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more numerous to look for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to Re/Max Bulgaria analysts, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and more and more of them are also buying in the a very inexpensive corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, retail and office space promises the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus to be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the country. &#39;year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria seek at the same time to change their life, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers fall into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional manager of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price varying between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are the easy access and the possibilities of communication, the proximity of a big city, the shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realizing a gain in the medium or long term.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly rising due to ever-increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, over the past 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percent
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the regime of the international climate after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians arriving from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, lively discussions are taking place on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that, for the moment, they did not wish to discuss exact figures, however that they were ready to sign an agreement on the reduction, until 2020, of greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent above the 1990 level.
Another important subject of the conference is to see if the developed countries commit themselves, apart from reducing emissions, to providing financial and technological assistance to the countries which need it.
An agreement was also signed concerning aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of directors composed of 16 members probably within the framework of the Global Environment Fund of the United Nations (GEF), communicated Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
Hungary&#39;s Six Percent
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Waters, confirms the EU&#39;s ambition to maintain its role as flagship in the global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new agreement internationally before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the &quot;Agreement after 2012”, and it was ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if the other major regions of the world and/or the developing countries were also ready to make commitments commensurate with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had aimed in total for a reduction of 5.2 percent and all of the 15 members of the EU at that time made the commitment out of 8 for hundred less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment .
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be implemented within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed until after 2012. In this In this case, reduction commitments below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which has been underlined in the new report by the IPCC, an international scientific body, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for addressing climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase in the Earth&#39;s average temperature of more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units share recordings made during their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site in a bid to make themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that was passionate about YouTube: the special units intervening in Afghanistan upload video sequences on the operations carried out against the Taliban since March 2006, announced the BBC.
These recordings, taken using miniature helmet-mounted cameras, are monitored at the air force&#39;s operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is essential
The air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this channel and their &quot;channel&quot; has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defense registered there under the name of &quot;defenceheadquarters&quot; in the spring of 2007 and it provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and international peacekeeping forces for Peace in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channel on YouTube.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the original purpose of the air force, the videos were posted on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they also served to inform the general public of the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
Propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements shown on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, defense consultant. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
Americans made a game
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are shown on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the &quot;official&quot; propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos had already passed on the net presenting the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan which were carried out in real mission, but the British army is carried away for the loading of these videos only recently.
Americans do recruiting a little differently using the free downloadable shootout game America&#39;s Army. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers within the framework of a more or less real simulation.
Christmas raffle and donuts in the ministries
