The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as days of rest.
Days of rest are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that is ending and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the revelers can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have in all eleven feasts marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the 1848 revolution, as is October 23, which is the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the incorporation of our state, May 1 is Labor Day, and on November 1 and 2, we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or even religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, depending on the calendar, it has become common to rearrange working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the party marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for long weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the long weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labor has ruled in special regulations on the days to replace the days preceding or following the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and to all their salaried employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions running without interruption and in service, by virtue of their vocation, and also for rest days.
This year, the working days will be modified only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life comes to a standstill almost in the whole country because according to experience the majority of people rather work overtime or take holidays they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year&#39;s Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday April 25 will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday May 2.
Another change is planned for October 23: Saturday October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year promises to be festive because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year&#39;s Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six trivial things that can annoy colleagues terribly
Emails that we forget to send, voicemails that we never receive, innocent lies that annoy us almost more: these are things that &quot;beautify&quot; the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether one gets used to these troubles or one takes up the challenge and consciously avoids ambiguous situations, causing trouble for others.
Examples.
“Excuse me, I forgot to tell you that we called you from the marketing department,” a colleague tells you.
That you missed an appointment?
At best he&#39;s sorry and tries to make things right by calling the marketing department to tell them he forgot to pass on the message (this is the least common solution).
In the majority of cases, the thing is arranged with an apology.
Before having painful explanations, it is useful to think about how you can cause unpleasant moments to your colleagues and to make efforts to avoid them.
Are you borrowing something that doesn&#39;t belong to you?
There&#39;s nothing more annoying than wanting to take a file, an office tool or the phone and you can&#39;t find it anywhere.
Do you remember how the night before you put the stapler on the desk but it disappeared the next morning?
Do you find your pen by chance that you thought was lost on your colleague&#39;s desk?
Don&#39;t take anything from your colleagues without asking otherwise they are right to be angry with you for stealing their property.
Do not bring back envelopes, post-it in your pocket because it can be annoying that there are no more and that you need them right away.
Do you gossip about the privacy of colleagues?
There are no good ways to stop gossip from spreading.
Who did what, with whom?
Where and why?
Do not tell everyone your information (assumptions) about the private lives of your colleagues!
If a colleague shares his intimate secrets with you, don&#39;t abuse his trust!
Bury the information shared in you and do not discuss it with your colleagues in his absence even if your colleagues are also aware.
Are you claiming to be ill without just cause?
When you call the office and claim to be ill on the pretext of a heartbreaking headache because you feel bad or think you need a rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent business, your missions have term must be done by someone else for you.
Don&#39;t bother your colleagues!
If you know in advance that the next day you won&#39;t be going to work or that something may happen that would force you to stay at home, don&#39;t forget to tell your boss and your colleagues to avoid surprise. of your absence the next day.
Humming, giggling, telephone
You immerse yourself in your work but the sneer of your colleagues tears you away brutally?
You became, unwittingly, a witness to a telephone discussion that you would have done better not to listen to?
Don&#39;t bother your co-workers with humming, humming, talking aloud (that you lead over their heads), kicking your feet, swearing or speaking out loud.
They can disturb even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
Do you blame others for a fault?
If your work is not done by the set deadline, you forget to send an important letter or message, do not blame anyone for this oversight!
Don&#39;t blame it on the potential chaos in the office or your noisy colleagues!
Admit it if you made a mistake and if it caused inconvenience to others, fix the mistake!
Ask how you could repair your fault, repair the negligence!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Wearing jogging and slippers is comfortable at home but they are not suitable for the office!
Do not put on comfortable jogging even if your function allows it!
Don&#39;t be neglected, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your job requires it, by putting on pretty and elegant clothes, to go to work!
