Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the English, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will thus be placed on the money markets through auctions.
The banks will have to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are ready to borrow money.
For example, the American Fed will auction 40 billion dollars and, in addition, it will provide 24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the attacks of September 11 that the Central Banks of individual States have decided on such concerted action, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
&quot;This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend&quot;, writes in his report to clients Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group.
&quot;The concerted action of central banks has reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,&quot; adds Baumohl in his report.
Banks have already lost 60 billion dollars because of defaulted loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts still expect further losses in the billions.
&quot;If central banks have chosen this approach, it is because they really need to understand what may still follow,&quot; said NBA chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
&quot;It seems that the situation is really bad,&quot; he adds.
Central banks fear that, if the banks themselves will have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the US economy into a recession that could affect economic growth worldwide.
Central Banks made this choice after they failed to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that the banks were still afraid of borrowing from each other, despite the fact that the American, Canadian and English central banks had lowered their interest rates on several occasions during the autumn.
&quot;It will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates,&quot; Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central banks&#39; approach will not help avert the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem, which is the fall in the real estate market in the USA.
