On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not only find this list in its entirety, but enriched.
However, there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island of the Greater Antilles.
In Spanish times, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the depot and transshipment point for the treasures the Spaniards had stolen and were transporting to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was erected at the very beginning of the 1920s.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who had it built, since everything that was a crime in the USA (especially under prohibition) was allowed and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling of chance, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, tall buildings have grown and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50s of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
Showbusiness stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
And today then?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita yourself.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be mixed with the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars are still circulating in Havana, since the once imported jigoulis and fiats have already long since rotted in such a salty and humid climate.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is noticeably decrepit, nowhere else in the vicinity are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings much-needed money, its development is given the green light.
During the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had been brought in from the extensive plantations in the sugar mills on a narrow gauge by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and it is thus that one can see small locomotives running there, the contemporaries of which are only in museums elsewhere.
