A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of linear space in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), have so far only been available for consultation for &quot;humanitarian&quot; purposes, i.e. individually and by name. at the request of a former victim or his heirs.
The eleven States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all the States being completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians&#39; access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to carry out research &quot;in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced laborers&quot;, explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of the deportation.
The registers of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labor and, possibly, to bring them proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, in 2006.
