The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine raises the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are transported by gas pipelines, and each conduit is scrupulously monitored.
kyiv has announced that if Russia raises the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two caused a decrease in supplies to EU countries
The latest spat between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia&#39;s owned monopoly company supplying the gas, tried unsuccessfully to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as planned after it agreed to pay for 2008 up to 50% more for gas supplies from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would mean a 40% increase in import costs for Ukraine from Gazprom.
“It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the conversations, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas passes,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told the news agency. Reuters.
“The fluctuations in gas costs would no doubt be linked to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine”
The last major altercation between Moscow and kyiv in January 2006 caused the interruption of supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine.
This caused exports to Western Europe to fall, thereby increasing prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of EU supplies.
Russia has the largest gas stocks, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
Consequently, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Union nations in Central Asia.
