Petite Sarre, good training.
The smallest federal state leads in professional training, and even shines with the international orientation of its colleges.
It is only in one area that a deficit weighs on the Saarland, similar to that of the rest of the country.
&quot;I explained yesterday for the 50th time to a non-Saar, that we are not French&quot; - this is the slogan that the smallest federated state, in self-mockery, displays for its 50th anniversary.
At this level, France and Luxembourg play a large role in the training system of Saarland, a system which is placed fifth in the training monitor of the Institute of German Economics in Cologne.
Thus, already by tradition, the higher education institutions cooperate closely with neighboring countries.
The university was founded in Saarbrücken in 1948 by the French.
To this day, students have the possibility of completing their studies there with a double or even a triple diploma.
This is evidenced by the high proportion of 15.6 per cent of foreign students.
Saarland also takes the country&#39;s children to college in above-average numbers - many of them without a gymnasium diploma.
&quot;In Saarland, we take advantage of the vocational training system&quot;, says Axel Plünnecke, training expert at IW.
More than one young person in five obtains their diploma in a vocational school, thus the Saarland is more than seven points above the national average.
Also the possibilities of combining professional and academic training are relatively well developed.
Considering the number of inhabitants, the dual degree program is the second best in Germany.
Despite practical training and growing demand, the number of engineering graduates has fallen by a third in recent years.
This is why the Saarland Ministry of Education has forced higher education institutions to launch a marketing campaign in engineering sciences.
&quot;After the first PISA studies, we celebrated a lot of reforms in general schools,&quot; said a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
Thus the government has introduced comparison tests throughout the federated state.
In order for the children to start learning earlier, the last year of crèche is free of charge - a model that other federal states are now also copying.
Only future comparison studies will be able to show whether student performance improves in a lasting way.
In the PISA studies in 2003, the proportion of students at risk was reduced from 29 to 20 percent.
Overall, however, Saarland has not improved as much as other federal states.
The Bavarians are doing better.
And to the chagrin of the Saar people, knowledge of foreign languages is not measured by the PISA studies - otherwise one could earn points in this area.
Because the language of the neighbor is compulsory in high schools - even if the Saarlanders are not French.
