Venus is Earth&#39;s infernal twin.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe &quot;Venus Express&quot; has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning on Venus.
The European probe &quot;Venus Express&quot; today provided proof of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus erupts at a height of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California at Los Angeles in the scientific magazine &quot;Nature&quot;.
According to the famous theory of love juice, the lightning would have brought life to Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans which led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: &quot;If there was life, it must have been at a very early date in history&quot;, explains Sean Solomon of the &quot;Carnegie Institution&quot; in Washington.
Today there should be hardly any living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
&quot;Venus may be Earth&#39;s hellish twin, but she&#39;s still a twin,&quot; said Russel.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of &quot;Venus Express&quot; in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no more probes had been on their way to explore this planet since the nineties.
According to the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several &quot;Nature&quot; articles do not only underline the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the points in common with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than supposed at first sight.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the swirls of wind already known at the North Pole, a swirl of clouds at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star orbits the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost to space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth as carbonate, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
