With &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; and &quot;Murderous Peace&quot;, two films deal again with the Balkan war.
But the two are not convincing.
Either the projects are based too much on action and insane exchanges of fire or, on the contrary, they are too tearful.
Here, even Richard Gere in &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; can&#39;t help.
The good news first: certainly the war criminals Karadzic and Mladic are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, but it is precisely there, in the darkest hinterland of the Bosnian war, that the actor Richard Gere is then found.
We had finally lost sight of the most handsome man of the eighties, because far too many nice and frivolous roles in sentimental films for women and far too many press conferences on the subject of Buddhism robbed him of the want to show off.
Today Richard Gere is suddenly the most important argument for watching &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; anyway - when the hunter becomes the hunted (why do today&#39;s films have to be as long and confusing as collective driver agreements locomotives?)
He delivers a magnificent portrayal full of winks: basically, his war reporter character Simon Hunt is what Gere might have become, if fate and the film industry weren&#39;t so benevolent: a man who has its best times long behind it, but which, even as a crumbling monument to its decline, still retains visible remnants of its former charm.
But despite this advantage, &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; continues together with the German production &quot;Murderous Peace&quot;, which is also released this week, the endless series of failed films on the Balkan war.
From &quot;Murderous Peace&quot; we can quickly make the trial: the film speaks of two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who save a Serbian woman from the Kosovar snipers, in which one of the two still quickly falls in love.
Although it is welcome that here the Serbs are for once not presented as the sole cause of all evil, this film as flat as a TV movie is lost far too quickly in the action and the insane exchanges of fire .
It remains a kind of &quot;Alarm for Cobra 11&quot; without a highway but with a war instead.
On the contrary, one can examine in the perfect example of &quot;The Hunting Party&quot;, why basically there was never a really good film about the Balkan war.
The story of the three American war reporters, who condition themselves to track the high war criminal &quot;the fox&quot;, could perhaps have become, with another director and another screenwriter (both at the same time Richard Shepard), another time a new &quot;Apocalypse Now&quot;.
Because the stories are strikingly similar: two males go as a small team into the forest, to accomplish something the military cannot do and for both males it becomes a journey into madness.
One of the reasons &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; fails is that Simon Hunt is simply not allowed to be the deserted cynic with a heart he is introduced to us at the start.
No, the script must additionally attribute to him a romantic affair with a Bosnian woman subsequently murdered.
Then &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; becomes definitely bad, when the reporter, in the space of the last five minutes, by a fast-track process, manages to do what NATO, the CIA and all the bounty hunters in the world have not succeeded in five years: catch the war criminal and leave him for a just revenge to the Bosnian Muslims.
It&#39;s so bad that we should seize the International Court of The Hague for crimes against cinematographic logic.
In this case, the film has too deep a human concern.
He wants to denounce that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and he suspects the Americans and the French (here they must exceptionally agree) of not conducting the hunt intensively enough because of secret political agreements.
But the well-intentioned and the wicked are so similar this time around that a famous poem by Brecht comes to mind.
This one speaks of a wooden mask of an Asian demon on the poet&#39;s work table: &quot;Compassionate, I see the veins in the forehead swollen, clearly: how tiring it is to be wicked.&quot;
Movies like &quot;The Hunting Party&quot; have exactly such tumescent heads, but hinting at how tiring it is to be good.
The problem is not limited to the genre of Balkan war films.
Recently, it was reported in this newspaper that all Hollywood films about Iraq were big flops.
We can add: there have never been any good films about South Africa.
Which applies every time: When a star drags on a hotbed or on a minefield, then something like &quot;Rangoon&quot; with Patricia Arquette, &quot;Jenseits aller Grenzen&quot; with Angelina Jolie or &quot;&quot;Blutdiamanten&quot; comes out with Leonardo DiCaprio.
It is possible that all of these conflicts are still simply too close in time.
Either way, decades still passed before Hollywood could make a good holocaust movie with &quot;Schindler&#39;s List.&quot;
Some films still have to mature - those which today are worth classic works on Vietnam &quot;The Deer Hunter&quot;, &quot;Apocalypse Now&quot; or &quot;Full Metal Jackett&quot; were by no means unanimously celebrated in their time as masterpieces.
But perhaps we now also know just too much about the conflicts of the world, where every slaughter happens live on two screens at the same time at home,
And that robs the screenwriters of the lack of scruples they need to tell great stories.
&quot;To Be or Not To Be&quot; or &quot;The Dictator&quot; actually got that good too because Lubtisch and Chaplin didn&#39;t yet know just how dominant the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you shouldn&#39;t want to be good when you want to make good movies.
Perhaps it is necessary to have the sarcastic and distanced artistic glance of the novelist Lawrence Norfolk.
When asked about the parallel between his historical novel &quot;Dictionnaire de Lemprière&quot; and the Balkan war, he replied: &quot;It&#39;s only because some things never change&quot;.
&quot;Big cities will always be horribly dangerous, men will always be horribly murdered and war will always reign in Yugoslavia.&quot;
