These are not the cases of Warhols.
Whoever connects the concepts Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or if?
Right now, wooden cases made in Sweden are casting shadows over the list of Warhol&#39;s works.
Many of the ninety &quot;Stockholm Type&quot; Brillo-Boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo-Boxes from the year 1968 a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot;, which the former museum director Pontus Hulten donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of &quot;Stockholm-type&quot; Brillo-Boxes, which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a bewildering chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot;, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of &quot;Brillo&quot; soap powder cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol&#39;s agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes which at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auctions, as authorized original Brillo-Boxes by Andy Wahrol , with the designation &quot;Type Stockholm&quot;.
Some of them have fetched over $100,000 at auction.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén wrongly claimed later that around one hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then ceded to him.
In truth, the 105 cases of Hultén were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
By this date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum&#39;s six Brillo-Boxes, three others from private Swedish collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies dating from the year 1990 reveals on the contrary that the paint was directly applied without primer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover it is not a question of an oil painting, but an acrylic.
&quot;These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes list&quot;, suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: &quot;If the &#39;Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board&#39; in New York does not come another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six cases in its collection as copies/exhibition material.&quot;
Already in July the Authentication Board has of course announced that it will investigate the &quot;heavy charges&quot; which will be raised in the case of the powdered soap boxes.
But since then we have been surrounded by an inexorable silence.
Manila Rebel Soldiers Surrender
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers give up, the same ones who had taken refuge in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chef Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the government had shortly before stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had entrenched themselves in the building for hours.
About half of them were standing in court on Wednesday due to a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly disappear with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who would normally have to watch them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined in his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to the government cordoned off the area around the respectable hotel.
The President called an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Advisor Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers&#39; action.
&quot;People are tired of it,&quot; said Trillanes.
&quot;We are calling on people to join us.&quot;
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite Scout Rangers unit, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already since 2003 the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The uprising broke down nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have already been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
